value.value: Anatomical structure that is an individual member of a species and consists of more than one cell.
The anterior division of the spider body.
The posterior division of the spider body.
The outer non-cellular layer of the integument formed by the epidermis.
The sclerite that covers the prosoma dorsally.
First opisthosomal segment, the narrowed connection between prosoma and opisthosoma.

Material anatomical entity in a gaseous, liquid, semisolid or solid state; produced by anatomical structures or derived from inhaled and ingested substances that have been modified by anatomical structures as they pass through the body.
Finger-like or conical silk spinning appendages located at the posterior end of the opisthosoma.
Any of the two main divisions of the whole organism formed from groups of segments.
Light sensing organ with a single lens.
The anterior appendage of a spider (the jaw) consisting of a large basal segment (paturon) and an apical fang.
The palp of the female.
Appendage of prosoma, between the palp and leg 2.
Appendage of prosoma, between the leg 1 and leg 3.
Appendage of prosoma, between the leg 2 and leg 4.
Most posterior appendage of prosoma.
Ventral sclerite on the pedicel.
The dorsal sclerite on the pedicel, or lorum. In many spiders the lorum is transversally divided into lorum 1 and lorum 2.
The booklung of the second opisthosomal segment.
The lateral spinneret of the fourth opisthosomal segment.
The median spinneret of the fifth opisthosomal segment.
The lateral spinneret of the fifth opisthosomal segment.
A small sclerite at the base of the chelicera, under the clypeus.
The dorsal sclerite of the anal tubercle.
The ventral sclerite of the anal tubercle.
The organ system of ectodermal origin consisting of cuticle and epidermis. It includes also sensory and glandular structures.

definition.value: The organ system that forms the covering layer of the animal.

value.value: The elements in the second and third segment of the opisthosoma of adult females, which are involved in copulation, sperm storage and fertilization.
The palp of the adult male, modified, with a copulatory organ attached to the tarsus.
The median of the anterior row.
The lateral eye of the anterior row.
The median eye of the posterior row.
The lateral eye of the posterior row.
A cord of silk composed by more than one silk fiber.
A single silk thread, produced by a single spigot.
A segment of the opisthosoma.
The booklung of the third opisthosomal segment.
A depression on the clypeus with glandular tissue.
A depression on the side of the carapace, above the palp, with pores, presumable gland openings.

A paired trachea arising between the two lateral respiratory structures. Median tracheae are derived from muscle apodemes (the 3rd opisthosomal entapophyses), and thus may retain a connection with the opisthosomal muscles at the tip.
The entapophysis of the third opisthosomal segment.
The apical segment of a chelicera, bearing the opening of the venom gland.
The basal segment of the chelicera.
The spiracle of the posterior booklung.
A leaf of the posterior booklung.
A small sclerite on the posterior end of the intercheliceral articulation, usually matching a small concavity on each paturon.
The basal, 1st segment of the female palp. It may be expanded in a lobe, and then is called endite.
The 2nd segment of the female palp, between coxa and femur.
The 3rd segment of the female palp, between trochanter and patella.
The 4th segment of the female palp, between femur and tibia.
The 5th segment of the female palp, between patella and tarsus.
